An unveiling ceremony was held in the front yard of the Chusenji Community Exchange Center, where local and government officials celebrated its completion.
Masujiro was a military scientist, a Western scholar, and a doctor during the end of the Edo period and the Meiji Restoration.
After teaching at the Bakufu's Bansho Shirabesho, a research and educational institution for Western studies, he opened a private school called Kyukyodo in Edo, where he taught Western studies, military science and medicine.
Even after returning to the Choshu Domain, he gave lectures on military science at Yamaguchi Meirinkan.
The bronze statue focused on Masujiro as an educator.
Standing beside the globe, holding a calligraphy in his hand, he gave a lecture on Western studies.
The statue, combined with the pedestal, is about 3 meters high (1.55 meters), and it is said that it was made from the perspective of a disciple taking Masujiro's lecture.
It was designed by Masujiro's wife, Takami Marie (27), a descendant of Kotoko and a local designer.
It was built by the project executive committee (Chairman Okamoto Satoshi) 150 years after the death of Omura Masujiro, whose parent organization is the Chusenji Residents' Association, soliciting donations.
Approximately 128 million yen was collected from 104 people nationwide.
The project cost, including the installation of famous boards, is approximately 12 million yen.
The surplus donations will be used to maintain and manage the statue.
Chairman Okamoto said, "Masujiro, who has continued to have high aspirations and made great contributions as an educator, is the pride of his old hometown and a bronze statue that will be the hope of the children of the region who will be responsible for the future."
